---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';

const title = 'CrossDrop vs AirDrop vs Nearby Share – The Cross-Platform AirDrop Alternative';
const description =
  'AirDrop is Apple-only and Quick Share (Nearby Share) is Android-first. CrossDrop works between Android, iPhone, Windows, and Mac in the browser — no app, no login, no contact sharing, no quality loss.';

const jsonLd = [
  {
    '@context': 'https://schema.org',
    '@type': 'BreadcrumbList',
    itemListElement: [
      { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 1, name: 'CrossDrop', item: 'https://crossdrop.app/' },
      { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 2, name: 'CrossDrop vs AirDrop', item: 'https://crossdrop.app/vs-airdrop' },
    ],
  },
];

const rows = [
  ['Android ↔ iPhone', '✅ Yes', '❌ Apple devices only', '⚠️ Limited (Android-first)'],
  ['Windows ↔ Mac', '✅ Yes', '❌ No', '⚠️ Windows app, no macOS'],
  ['Works in the browser', '✅ Yes — nothing to install', '❌ Built into the OS', '❌ App / OS feature'],
  ['Account required', '✅ None', '⚠️ Apple ID', '⚠️ Google account for some modes'],
  ['Contact list access', '✅ Never', '⚠️ Contact-based discovery', '⚠️ Contact-based discovery'],
  ['Original quality guaranteed', '✅ Byte-for-byte', '✅ Yes', '✅ Yes'],
  ['Discovery / visibility settings', '✅ None needed — explicit QR/code pairing', '⚠️ "Who can see me" settings', '⚠️ Device visibility settings'],
  ['Files touch a server', '✅ Never', '✅ No', '⚠️ Some fallback modes'],
];
---

<Base {title} {description} {jsonLd}>
  <article class="wrap article">
    <p class="eyebrow">Comparison</p>
    <h1>CrossDrop vs AirDrop vs Quick Share</h1>
    <p class="lede">
      AirDrop is excellent — inside Apple's walls. Quick Share (formerly
      Nearby Share) covers the Android side. The moment your two devices sit
      on different sides of that wall, both leave you re-compressing photos
      through WhatsApp or emailing files to yourself. CrossDrop exists for
      exactly that moment.
    </p>

    <div class="table-scroll">
      <table class="compare">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Capability</th>
            <th scope="col">CrossDrop</th>
            <th scope="col">Apple AirDrop</th>
            <th scope="col">Quick Share</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {rows.map(([cap, cd, ad, ns]) => (
            <tr>
              <th scope="row">{cap}</th>
              <td>{cd}</td>
              <td>{ad}</td>
              <td>{ns}</td>
            </tr>
          ))}
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h2>No contact sharing — pairing is explicit</h2>
    <p>
      AirDrop and Quick Share discover nearby people through your contacts,
      Apple ID, or device visibility settings — which is exactly how
      strangers end up in your share sheet and why "who can see me" settings
      exist at all. CrossDrop has no discovery. Nobody can see your device.
      A connection only exists when you deliberately share a QR code or room
      code with the other device, and it dies the moment you're done.
    </p>

    <h2>No quality loss — unlike the usual workarounds</h2>
    <p>
      The common cross-platform workarounds all degrade your media:
      messaging apps recompress photos and videos aggressively, email caps
      attachment sizes, and cloud round-trips are slow and often transcode.
      CrossDrop sends the original file, byte for byte, at local Wi-Fi
      speed.
    </p>

    <h2>When AirDrop is still the right tool</h2>
    <p>
      Honest answer: if both devices are Apple and near each other, AirDrop
      is seamless and works offline without any setup. CrossDrop is the tool
      for every other combination — mixed households, Android-to-iPhone
      photo handoffs, moving files onto a work Windows laptop, or sharing
      with someone whose contact you don't have (and don't want to add).
    </p>

    <p class="cta-row">
      <a class="btn btn-primary" href="/#transfer">Send a file with CrossDrop</a>
      <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/how-it-works">See how it works</a>
    </p>
  </article>
</Base>

<style>
  .article { max-width: 48rem; padding-block: clamp(2.5rem, 6vw, 4.5rem); }
  .lede { font-size: 1.15rem; color: var(--ink-soft); }
  .article h2 { margin-top: 2.25rem; }
  .table-scroll { overflow-x: auto; margin-block: 1.5rem; }
  table.compare th[scope='row'] { font-weight: 600; }
  .cta-row { display: flex; gap: 0.75rem; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-top: 2.5rem; }
</style>
